  "name": "The Inner Triangle — Emotion, Cognition & Behavior in Relation",
  "description": "A 68-card oracle deck mapping the CBT triangle — Feel, Think, Do — placed in the relational field. Every emotion asks: what does your partner see? Every thought asks: what would their version be? Every behavior asks: what does it trigger across from you? 3 suits (Emotions, Cognitions, Behaviors), 14 L2 named triangles mapping specific loops (The Anxious Triangle, The Avoidant Triangle, The Shame-Hide Triangle, The Vulnerability-Connection Triangle), and 4 L3 meta-patterns. Companion grammar to Relationship Cards.\n\nGrounded in CBT (Beck), DBT (Linehan), EFT (Johnson), attachment theory (Bowlby), affect theory (Tomkins), schema therapy (Young), polyvagal theory (Porges), and mentalization (Fonagy).\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Edvard Munch's expressionist paintings of emotion — 'The Scream' (1893), 'Anxiety' (1894), 'Melancholy' (1894-96), 'Jealousy' (1895). Käthe Kollwitz's charcoal drawings of grief, tenderness, and maternal emotion (1900s-1930s). Francisco Goya's 'Black Paintings' (1819-1823) — Saturn, the dog, the witches' sabbath. William Blake's illustrations of states of being from 'Songs of Innocence and Experience' (1789-1794). Honoré Daumier's lithographs of human expression and social emotion (1830s-1870s). Charles Le Brun's 'Conference on Expression' (1668) — systematic drawings of facial expressions mapping emotion to physiology.",
  "grammar_type": "tarot",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "creator_link": "https://lifeisprocess.substack.com/",
